{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:04:37.536163+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's a walkthrough of the three database migrations in this repository, in the order they would be applied:\n\n---\n\n### Migration 1: `001_create_users.sql`\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n**What it does:** Creates the `users` table, the foundational entity of the application. It has:\n- `id` — an auto-incrementing 64-bit primary key (`BIGSERIAL`).\n- `email` — a unique, non-null text field for the user's email address.\n- `display_name` — an optional text field for a human-friendly name.\n- `created_at` — a timestamp with timezone that defaults to the current time when a row is inserted.\n\n---\n\n### Migration 2: `002_create_sessions.sql`\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n**What it does:** Creates the `sessions` table for managing user login sessions. It has:\n- `id` — a UUID serving as the primary key (likely used as the session token).\n- `user_id` — a foreign key referencing `users(id)`. The `ON DELETE CASCADE` clause ensures that if a user is deleted, all their sessions are automatically removed.\n- `issued_at` — timestamp when the session was created, defaults to `now()`.\n- `expires_at` — a required timestamp indicating when the session becomes invalid. (The application layer would enforce the expiry check.)\n\n---\n\n### Migration 3: `003_add_session_index.sql`\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n**What it does:** Adds a B-tree index on the `user_id` column of the `sessions` table. This speeds up queries that look up all sessions belonging to a specific user (e.g., \"find all active sessions for user X\" or cleanup operations that cascade from the `users` table).\n\n---\n\n### Summary of the migration chain\n\n| Order | File | Purpose |\n|-------|------|---------|\n| 1 | `001_create_users.sql` | Bootstraps the `users` table |\n| 2 | `002_create_sessions.sql` | Adds session tracking, dependent on `users` |\n| 3 | `003_add_session_index.sql` | Optimises session lookups by user |\n\nThese are plain SQL files with numeric prefixes, suggesting they are intended to be run sequentially with a simple migration runner (or manually) rather than through a framework like ActiveRecord or Alembic. No down/rollback migrations are present.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 885, "prompt_tokens": 5231, "total_tokens": 6116, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 280, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 4864}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 4864, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 367}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-pro", "system_fingerprint": "fp_9954b31ca7_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "3fcd0b24-7b8d-4493-847b-2eff985484a4", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3e6-ba1d-7481-bd6c-e8ac2ae175ae-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 5231, "output_tokens": 885, "total_tokens": 6116, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 4864}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 280}}}}]}}}
